    "Scale-out increases cluster parallelism but also increases consensus overhead, tail latency, network saturation, compaction backlog, and the likelihood of disruptive data rebalances.",
    "Scale-up improves per-node throughput and reduces local contention, but offers no relief for hotspots spread across partitions and eventually hits hardware ceilings.",
    "Workload Diversity Demands Multi-Dimensional ReasoningApplications exhibit widely varying characteristics:• read-heavy workloads with skewed access distributions,• write-intensive workloads sensitive to commit latency, • mixed workloads with large working sets,• workloads with diurnal patterns or unpredictable surges.",
    "A scaling policy that works for CPU-saturated workloads can fail disastrously for memory-bound workloads.",
    "A policy that works for strong-consistency write-heavy loads (e.g., Spanner) may be inefficient for eventually consistent KV systems (e.g., Dynamo).We show that many workloads benefit from coordinated, not independent, adjustments in horizontal and vertical resources."
